<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-846-694  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 846 694.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Learning  Oct 1989 v9 n2 p52(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How to take advantage of aging technology. (The CommodoreDistrict)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Leonard, Jenelle.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Aging software and hardware is a problem facing many schooldistricts.andP;  School technology budgets are increasingly eaten up bymaintaining and supporting existing technology, with nothing leftover for new technology purchases.andP;  Just when exciting new thingsare coming out, such as laserdiscs, networks, integrated learningsystems, and multimedia projects, technology budgets are static.andO;The slowdown, however, can be put to good use by encouragingteachers to use the technology that already exists.andP;  Improvingexisting instructional computing programs is one way ofcapitalizing on the current equipment, which may still go unusedby some teachers.andP;  This is what the District of Columbia PublicSchools is doing.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Secondary SchoolsEducational SoftwareMicrocomputersUser Training.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>